QUESTION 2: Normalize into 2nd Normal Form
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Given Table:
┌───────┬─────────────┬────────────────┬──────┐
│ Empno │ Training    │ Training_Date  │ Dept │
├───────┼─────────────┼────────────────┼──────┤
│ 101   │ Oracle SQL  │ 12-Aug-2015    │ TT   │
├───────┼─────────────┼────────────────┼──────┤
│ 101   │ Java        │ 21-Aug-2015    │ BU   │
├───────┼─────────────┼────────────────┼──────┤
│ 102   │ Oracle SQL  │ 18-Sep-2014    │ TT   │
└───────┴─────────────┴────────────────┴──────┘

Primary Key: (Empno, Training) — composite, since one employee can
attend many trainings.

Why it's not normalized:
Dept depends only on Empno, not on the full key (Empno, Training). An
employee's department doesn't change depending on which training they
take — this is a partial dependency, so the table violates 2NF.

Output Table 1 — EMPLOYEE:
┌───────┬──────┐
│ Empno │ Dept │
├───────┼──────┤
│ 101   │ TT   │
├───────┼──────┤
│ 102   │ TT   │
└───────┴──────┘

Output Table 2 — TRAINING:
┌───────┬─────────────┬────────────────┐
│ Empno │ Training    │ Training_Date  │
├───────┼─────────────┼────────────────┤
│ 101   │ Oracle SQL  │ 12-Aug-2015    │
├───────┼─────────────┼────────────────┤
│ 101   │ Java        │ 21-Aug-2015    │
├───────┼─────────────┼────────────────┤
│ 102   │ Oracle SQL  │ 18-Sep-2014    │
└───────┴─────────────┴────────────────┘


